habitat_description:
The eastern patch-nose snake occurs from southeastern Arizona, New Mexico, and central Texas into a significant portion of northern Mexico. Isolated populations have been reported in Oak Creek Canyon, Arizona. Most reports in the western range include populations above 1370 meters, but it has been also reported at elevations up to 1980 meters in more eastern localities (Stebbins 2003). This species uses soil to burrow, but also ground litter and fallen logs. The habitat has been described to be dominated by desert, grassland, shrubland, chaparral, cropland, and woodland. Populations occur in rocky canyons, mountain slopes with open woodland, plateaus, ponderosa pine forests, prairies, arid shrublands, oak-juniper savavanna, farmland, and thorn brush woodland (Degenhardt et al. 1996; Ernst and Ernst 2003; Stebbins 2003; Tennant 1998).

SW	-Plant associations consist of shrubland, oak-juniper savanna, thorn brush woodland, ponderosa pine forest, and woodland grassland patches.
